  <h1 id="page_title_padded">Pitching an Article</h1>

  <p>You may write an article on anything that fits into a category and meets our content policy below.
     If you're not sure what to write about, it is recommended to claim a pitch from our editors <%= link_to "here", pitches_path %>.</p>

  <p>Our editors reserve the right to reject any pitch that does not meet the below criteria. To pitch a new article topic, go <a target="_blank" href="/pitches/new">here</a>.</p>

  <h3 id="topic-requirements">Content requirements</h3>

  <p>An article or pitch will not be approved if it:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Depicts, contains, or provides access to violent content or threatens physical harm to a particular individual or group</li>
    <li>Is pornographic or obscene</li>
    <li>Contains copyrighted content</li>
  </ul>
  <p>This includes any pitches that directly deal with or report on violence, sex, drugs, or otherwise fit into any of the above categories.</p>
  <p>Any articles/pitches that are approved/published and go against these policies will be immediately taken down. The Teen Magazine also has the right to remove any writers or editors who repeatedly ignore these content policies.</p>
  <h5 id="topic-requirements"><b>The topic should be relevant to a teenage audience</b></h5>
  <p>Any article that is pitched should be specifically made for a teenage audience. This means it addresses a topic, experience, and/or problem that is felt by, or of interest to, some or most teens. It is not enough for the article to be of interest to some teens just because the topic has such a broad audience already (see diagram).</p>
  <%= image_tag("specificity_diagram.png", class: "image_fit_scrn") %>
  <p>It can be helpful to keep some notes on your phone to jot down ideas for article topics. If you are currently in, or just graduated, high school, think about your daily life and the things that you are struggling with. What excites you? What scares you? What would you love to learn more about?
    Chances are your daily life is made up of experiences similar to those of lots of other teens your age. What you wonder about, what sparks your curiosity, what worries you, what stresses you out, are common experiences and should be drawn upon when thinking of new topics. Keep in mind that any article topic you pitch should fall in one of these categories:</p>

  <div class="categories">
    <% @categories.each do |category| %>
      <p><%= link_to category.name, category, target: "_blank" %></p>
    <% end %>
  </div>

  <p>If you are still struggling to think of new topic ideas and your own life and those of your friends aren't enough inspiration, take a look at this video which explains how you can find topic ideas via <a target="_blank" href="https://www.quora.com/"><b>Quora.com</b></a>. Of course, it isn't necessary to write a response post on Quora (as talked about in the video below), but questions on the platform asked about friendships, high school, self-worth and identity, studying, applying to colleges,
    dealing with parental expectations, mental health in teenage years etc., can be very useful starting points. <a target="_blank" href="https://www.reddit.com/"><b>Reddit.com</b></a> can also be a great source of inspiration for article ideas when used in the same way.</p>

