  <h3 id="title-requirements">The title should be shareable and/or searchable</h3>

  <p>A title is shareable if it is interesting and can reasonably spark curiosity and/or some other emotion. Some great examples of shareable titles are "How Dressing Like Blair Waldorf Helped Me Take My SATs," "The Stages of All High School Relationships from an Outsider," "Why You Might Find It Hard to Make Deep Friendships," while vague, non-specific titles such as "Loving Your Body" does not fit this specification. If you are not sure, use the headline analyzer tool found here: <a href="https://aminstitute.com/headline/"><b>https://aminstitute.com/headline/</b></a>. Nine times out of ten, a shareable title should have an Emotional Marketing Value (EMV) score over 30. However, this measure is a tool, not the rule. If the title is only a few words, this headline analyzer is not reliable and the title is likely not interesting enough. Rely on your intuition and common sense in addition to the EMV score. </p>

  <p>
    A title is searchable if it contains keywords/phrases that would be reasonably typed into Google search. These titles are often questions, short responses, lists, etc. The topic should be specific enough that The Teen Magazine can come up in Google search. For example, “Cutest High School Romance Movies That Will Make You Cry” includes the keyword phrase "High School Romance Movies" which is a lot more specific than just “Best Netflix Movies." Using the strategies in the above paragraph can also help increase the liklihood someone on Google will actually click on your article (including "Cutest" and "Will Make You Cry" in the title). When doing this, make sure that the entire title will still show up in Google by using the <a target="_blank" href="https://moz.com/learn/seo/title-tag"><b>Moz SEO Tool</b></a>.
  </p>

  <h3 id="thumbnail-requirements">Thumbnail image requirements</h3>
  <p>
    First and foremost, the thumbnail image should meet The Teen Magazine's <a href="/image-policy" target="_blank">image policy</a>. We take copyright extremely seriously at The Teen Magazine, and failure to follow the image policy will result in your removal from The Teen Magazine.
    If there is anything unclear, it is your responsibilty to message in the Discord <b>#ask-editors</b> chat.
  </p>

  <p>The thumbnail image should also be relevant to the topic, not grainy, not cropped in a weird way, and not contain a mostly white background.</p>

